Package com.rb.nonbiz.util

Class EnumStringRoundTripConversionInfo<E extends java.lang.Enum<E> & JsonRoundTripStringConvertibleEnum<E>>

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.util.EnumStringRoundTripConversionInfo<E>
public class EnumStringRoundTripConversionInfo<E extends java.lang.Enum<E> & JsonRoundTripStringConvertibleEnum<E>>
extends java.lang.Object
Contains information about how to convert an enum (the 'convertible' kind, i.e. JsonRoundTripStringConvertibleEnum) back and forth from a unique (i.e. no two enum values share the same) and stable (i.e. does not depend on Java reflection information that can change if we change the code) string representation.

Strictly speaking, this only converts from a string to an enum value; the opposite is trivial, because one can always invoke JsonRoundTripStringConvertibleEnum.toUniqueStableString() on the enum value to find the string.

Although we could always instantiate one of these on the fly, it's probably best practice to have a static final object of this type inside every JsonRoundTripStringConvertibleEnum, and expose a static method to convert a string to an enum value, which then calls getEnumValue(String). We can't enforce this across enums by making them implement some interface, because we're talking about a static method, and static methods can't be part of an interface. But it can be a good convention.
